post_text:
Good Afternoon:

Homecoming football games are scheduled to be played on September 18th at Cascade High School and September 25th at Western Dubuque High School. Unfortunately, with the continued high positivity rates in our county we are cancelling all of the traditional activities that happen during homecoming week. We will not hold the powder puff game, the community pep assembly, the parade, or the homecoming dance this year. I know this news is disappointing to so many people, but the decision to cancel these activities is based solely on the safety of our students, staff, and communities. If things improve later in the year, we might be able to hold some of these activities in the spring of the school year. The administrators will be working with their student leaders to come up with possible options.

Thank you and take care of yourself and your family.

Rick Colpitts, Superintendent

post_text:
Good Morning:

As our district continues to prepare for the 2020-2021 school year, we want to make sure we have a solid plan for distance learning in case we have another extended school closure next year. In order to solidify our planning process, we need your help. We are asking all families to complete a technology survey to help us determine the technology gap that currently exists in our school system. With this information we will work on a plan to close the gap so that distance learning can happen in the future if it is needed. Please take a few minutes to complete this short survey by May 11th. (See survey links below.)

English: https://forms.office.com/Pages/ResponsePage.aspx?id=FbiVqdfvlU6H4g6JaorMAE2Et584qjlAjwlzVdnvOxlUQ0k5OExTQTRFM0RSM1hYR1RBV1hZOFJLNC4u

Spanish: https://forms.office.com/Pages/ResponsePage.aspx?id=FbiVqdfvlU6H4g6JaorMAE2Et584qjlAjwlzVdnvOxlURThBV1ZQVjMxSURZUkc2SVNaS0hSUFpaRi4u

Thank you,

Rick Colpitts, Superintendent
Western Dubuque Community School District

post_text:
We are aware that the federal guidelines requiring us to only serve lunches out of communities that meet certain requirements has caused hardship on families that do not live in those communities. By working with multiple partnerships outside of the school district, we have been able to secure more locations for bagged lunches. Project Rooted out of Dubuque is providing lunch from 11:30-12:30 Monday-Friday in the parking lots of Western Dubuque High School in Epworth, DMIS in Farley, and Peosta Elementary in Peosta.

We will continue to provide district lunches at our locations in Dyersville and Cascade as well.

These additional locations will be added starting Monday, March 23rd and operate until further notice. Pull up between the hours of 11:30 AM-12:30 PM for a bagged lunch based on Project Rooted 2 week rotational menu, or continue to get District provided lunches in Dyersville and Cascade from 11:30-12:30. #wdbqschools

post_text: 150 meals were served to children today in our Dyersville and Cascade locations despite unfavorable weather conditions. Hope to see you all back tomorrow. Our Nutrition Department is only allowed to use it's federal funding to serve meals in areas that are designated as in need. The only 2 areas that qualify in our district are located in the Dyersville and Casacde area that we have these sites. The district is also working with outside organizations, who do not have to follow federal guidelines, to try and get other pick-up sites added. Stay posted as these will be announced if and when they are created.

post_text: The girls basketball team at Cascade High School has had an impressive run over the past several years. This video from Iowa PBS shows many of the highlights. Congratulations on a fourth straight semi-final appearance in the state tournament. #wdbqschools
shared_text:
Iowa PBS
March 6 at 1:02 PM ·

The Cascade Junior-Senior High School Cougars are no strangers at the Wells Fargo Arena. Led by long time coach Mike Sconsa, the 2A school has made it to tournament play seven of the last eight years, winning it all in 2018. Coming off the team's first undefeated season, the Cougars' four returning seniors hope to make one final run at state tournament glory. #iowapbssports

post_text:
The latest Iowa School Performance Profile results have been released and we are incredibly proud of our schools. The Iowa School Performance Profile is an online tool showing how public schools performed on required measures. The website was developed to meet both federal and state requirements for publishing online school report cards. Their are six rankings including: exceptional, high performing, commendable, acceptable, needs improvement, and priority/comprehensive. All schools within the district scored in the top three categories with the specific results included below. These results are a testament to our dedicated staff, wonderful students, supportive families, and thriving communities. #wdbqschools

Farley Elementary: Exceptional
Cascade Elementary: Exceptional
Epworth Elementary: High Performing
Peosta Elementary: High Performing
Western Dubuque High School: High Performing
Cascade Junior/Senior High School: High Performing
Drexler Middle Intermediate: Commendable
Dyersville Elementary: Commendable

shared_text:
Western Dubuque High School
October 14, 2019 at 12:26 PM ·

Belin-Blank Center Honors Students and Teachers

Schuyler Ridenour of Durango and a student at Western Dubuque High School was among over 500 students from Iowa and throughout the nation who were recently invited to be honored at the University of Iowa Belin-Blank Center's Recognition Ceremony. Additionally, recognized students were given the opportunity to honor a teacher they credited for having a profound influence on their lives. Ridenour selected Mrs. Peggy Keegan of Dyersville for this honor.

The ceremony was held Sunday, October 6, 2019, at the Iowa Memorial Union on the University of Iowa campus. #wdbobcats
